# Importing necessary libraries
import pickle
from sklearn.linear_model import ElasticNet

# Removing rows with missing values from 'test' and 'train' DataFrames
test_na = test.dropna()
train_na = train.dropna()

# Concatenating the cleaned DataFrames into 'total_df'
total_df = pd.concat([train_na, test_na], ignore_index=True)

# Dropping columns 'galactic year', 'galaxy', and 'y' from the 'total_df' DataFrame
total_df.drop(['galactic year', 'galaxy', 'y'], axis=1, inplace=True)

# Calculating correlation matrix for features in 'total_df'
corrMatrix = total_df.corr()

# Plotting a heatmap to visualize the correlation matrix
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 20))
sns.heatmap(corrMatrix, annot=False)
plt.show()

# Setting correlation and missing value thresholds
koef_corr = 0.65
koef_na = 0.8
top_features = 5
num_model = 1
list_target_features = []
list_corr_features = []

# Iterating through columns to identify correlated features
for big_col in list(total_df.columns):
    list_correlated = []
    correlations = []
    na_rows = []
    na_big_col = total_df_fillna[big_col].isna().sum()

    # Checking correlation with other columns
    for col in list(total_df.columns):
        cor = total_df[big_col].corr(total_df[col])

        # Filtering based on correlation and excluding self-correlation
        if np.absolute(cor) > koef_corr and np.absolute(cor) < 0.99:
            list_correlated.append(col)
            correlations.append(np.absolute(cor))
            na_rows.append(total_df_fillna[col].isna().sum())

    # Creating a DataFrame to store correlated features, their correlations, and missing values
    df = pd.DataFrame(list(zip(list_correlated, correlations, na_rows)),
                      columns=['features', 'correlation', 'na'])

    # Filtering features with missing values below a threshold
    df = df[df.na < koef_na * na_big_col].sort_values(by='correlation', ascending=False)

    # Selecting the top correlated features
    list_correlated = list(df[:top_features].features)

    # Storing selected features and training ElasticNet model
    if len(list_correlated) > 0:
        list_target_features.append(big_col)
        list_corr_features.append(list_correlated)
        model = ElasticNet(random_state=42)
        model.fit(total_df[list_correlated], total_df[big_col])

        # Saving the model using pickle
        pkl_filename = "pickle_model_%i.pkl" % len(list_target_features)
        with open(pkl_filename, 'wb') as file:
            pickle.dump(model, file)

        num_model = num_model + 1
In [ ]:
# Looping through the saved models and making predictions for missing values
for i in range(len(list_target_features)):
    target = list_target_features[i]
    corr_feat = list_corr_features[i]

    # Loading the saved ElasticNet model using pickle
    with open("pickle_model_%i.pkl" % (i + 1), 'rb') as file:
        pickle_model = pickle.load(file)

    # Iterating through rows in the 'total_df_fillna' DataFrame
    for i in range(len(total_df_fillna.index)):
        time_corr_features = []

        # Extracting features for the current row
        for j in range(len(corr_feat)):
            if len(total_df_fillna[corr_feat[j]][i].shape) == 1:
                feat = total_df_fillna[corr_feat[j]][i].values[0]
            else:
                feat = total_df_fillna[corr_feat[j]][i]
            time_corr_features.append(feat)

        # Checking for missing values in the selected features
        if np.isnan(time_corr_features).sum() == 0:
            # Making predictions only for rows with missing values in the target column
            if np.isnan(total_df_fillna[target][i]) == True:
                pred = pickle_model.predict(np.asarray(time_corr_features).reshape(1, -1))
                total_df_fillna[target][i] = pred

# Checking the total number of missing values after imputation
print(total_df_fillna.isna().sum().sum())

# Creating new train and test DataFrames from 'total_df_fillna'
new_train = total_df_fillna[:len(train.index)].reset_index()
new_test = total_df_fillna[len(train.index):].reset_index()

# Joining original 'galactic year', 'galaxy', and 'y' columns to the new train DataFrame
new_train = new_train.join(train[['galactic year', 'galaxy', 'y']])

# Joining original 'galactic year' and 'galaxy' columns to the new test DataFrame
new_test = new_test.join(test[['galactic year', 'galaxy']])

# Concatenating new train and test DataFrames into a single DataFrame 'df'
df = pd.concat([new_train, new_test], ignore_index=True)

# Sorting the DataFrame by 'galaxy' and 'galactic year'
df_sort = df.sort_values(by=['galaxy', 'galactic year'], ascending=True, ignore_index=True)

# Creating a list of unique galaxies
title_galaxy = list(df['galaxy'].unique())

# Getting numeric column names
num_col = df.iloc[:, :-3].columns

# Initializing an empty DataFrame to store the final imputed values
total_df = pd.DataFrame()

# Iterating through each galaxy
for name in title_galaxy:
    # Selecting rows for the current galaxy
    temp = df[df['galaxy'] == name]

    # Interpolating missing values using linear interpolation and filling remaining missing values with mean
    for column in num_col:
        if temp[column].isna().sum() + 4 <= len(temp):
            temp[column] = temp[column].interpolate(method='linear', limit_direction='backward')
        if temp[column].isna().sum() < len(temp):
            m = temp[column].mean()
            temp[column] = temp[column].fillna(m)

    # Concatenating the imputed values for the current galaxy to the final DataFrame
    total_df = pd.concat([total_df, temp], ignore_index=True)

# Checking the total number of missing values after imputation
print(total_df.isna().sum().sum())

from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Define hyperparameters to tune

    'learning_rate': [0.01, 0.1, 0.2],
    'max_depth': [3, 5, 7],
    'n_estimators': [50, 100, 200]
}

# Perform grid search for hyperparameter tuning

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
